Statistical model

Statistical model

\[\textrm{outcome}_i = \textrm{model} + \textrm{error}_i \]

  • A simple linear regression model: \(y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \epsilon_i\)
  • A non-linear regression model: \(y_i = f(x_i) + \epsilon_i\)
  • \(\cdots\)

Modeling

Measuring the “Fit” of the Model

  • Calculating “Error”
  • A deviation is the difference between the mean and an actual data point.
  • errors can be calculated by taking each value and subtracting the fit from it: \[ \textrm{error}_i = \textrm{observed}_i - \textrm{fitted value}_i \]

Mean model

\[\textrm{outcome}_i = \textrm{mean} + \textrm{error}_i \]

  • What we assume?
    • We observe the values varying around the mean.
  • How do we estimate the mean?
    • We use the sample mean – the sum of all scores divided by the number of scores.
  • Your “prediction” for the next observation is simply the sample mean.
  • Why does it make sense?
    • The mean is also the value from which the (squared) scores deviate least.

Why squared?

  • We could just take the error between the mean and the data and add them, but:
Score Mean Deviation
1 2.6 -1.6
2 2.6 -0.6
3 2.6 0.4
3 2.6 0.4
4 2.6 1.4

Total error is: \(-1.6 -0.6 + 0.4 + 0.4 + 1.4 = 0\).

Sum of Squared Errors

  • We could add the deviations to find out the total error.
  • Deviations cancel out because some are positive and others negative.
  • Therefore, we square each deviation.
  • If we add these squared deviations we get the sum of squared errors (SS).
Score Mean Deviation Squared Deviation
1 2.6 -1.6 2.56
2 2.6 -0.6 0.36
3 2.6 0.4 0.16
3 2.6 0.4 0.16
4 2.6 1.4 1.96

SS: \(2.56 + 0.36 + 0.16 + 0.16 + 1.96 = 5.20\).

Variance

  • The sum of squares is a good measure of overall variability, but is dependent on the number of scores.
  • We calculate the average variability by dividing by the number of scores (\(n\)).
  • This value is called the variance (\(s^2\)).

\[ \textrm{variance } s^2 = \frac{SS}{N-1} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N} (x_i - \bar{x})^2}{N-1} \]

  • We divide by \(N-1\) – it is called degree of freedom (DF).

Note

  • When \(N\) is very large, it makes little difference whether we use \(N\) or \(N-1\).

  • In general statistical model setting, we use \[ \frac{SS}{DF} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N} (y_i - \hat{f}(x_i))^2}{DF} \] and this is a measure of variability of \(y_i\) around \(f(x_i)\).

  • This is called Mean Squared Error (MSE).

Standard Deviation

  • The variance has one problem: it is measured in units squared.
  • This isn’t a very meaningful metric so we take the square root value.
  • This is the standard deviation (\(s\)).

\[ s = \sqrt{\frac{SS}{N-1} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N} (x_i - \bar{x})^2}{N-1}} \]

  • Similarly, we also take the square root of MSE – RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error).
    • This metric is often used as a key performance measure to compare different models.

Population and Samples

  • Population
    • The collection of units (be they people, plankton, plants, cities, suicidal authors, etc.) to which we want to generalize a set of findings or a statistical model
  • Sample
    • A smaller (but hopefully representative) collection of units from a population used to determine truths about that population

Statistics is about how to use sample to learn about population.

An example – a (typical) building energy consumption pattern

Observed data

Fitted

Confidence Intervals (CI)

  • An interval estimated from the observed data, that might contain the true value of an unknown population parameter.
  • The sample mean calculated from a sample of size \(n\) is approximately normal under random sampling: \[ \bar{X} \sim N \left(\mu, \frac{\sigma^2}{n} \right) \]

A simple example

(No worry if you don’t know how to read the code)

  • We have a group of 10000 people whose average age is 49.52 and standard deviation 28.81.
  • If we choose a sample of size 100, the sample mean age varies:
mean(sample(age, 100))
## [1] 52.58787
mean(sample(age, 100))
## [1] 48.04008
  • So let’s repeat 10000 times and store it as xbar.
xbar <- replicate(10000, mean(sample(age, 100)))

mean(xbar)
## [1] 49.54076
sd(xbar) 
## [1] 2.870483
28.81 / sqrt(100) # sigma / sqrt(n)
## [1] 2.881

Test Statistics

  • A statistic for which the frequency of particular values is known; its sampling distribution under the null hypothesis must be calculable (at least approximately).
  • Often defined as a ratio of signal to noise: \[ \textrm{test statistic} = \frac{\textrm{variance explained by the model}}{\textrm{variance not explained by the model}} = \frac{\textrm{effect}}{\textrm{error}} \]

One- and Two-Tailed Tests

Type I and Type II Errors

  • Type I error
    • occurs when we believe that there is a genuine effect in our population when, in fact, there isn’t (i.e., false positive)
    • The probability is the \(\alpha\)-level (usually .05)
  • Type II error
    • occurs when we believe that there is no effect in the population when, in reality, there is (i.e., false negative)
    • The probability is the \(\beta\)-level (often .2)
